    "summary": "The Iran-backed Houthi group launched drones and missiles at Abha International Airport in southwestern Saudi Arabia, breaking an unofficial ceasefire that had held since 2022. The attack marks the most serious escalation in cross-border hostilities in four years.",
    "content": "On July 14, 2026, the Iran-aligned Houthi movement carried out a coordinated drone and missile strike on Abha International Airport in southwestern Saudi Arabia. The attack ended a four-year period of relative calm along the Saudi-Yemeni border, following an informal ceasefire that had been in place since 2022.\n\nThe Houthis claimed the assault was in retaliation for a Saudi airstrike on Sanaa International Airport in Yemen, which they said occurred earlier this month. Saudi authorities have not confirmed the alleged strike, but regional observers note that the exchange signals a dangerous uptick in tensions between the two sides.\n\nAbha Airport, a civilian facility that also serves military purposes, was previously targeted by Houthi attacks in 2019 and 2020. The latest incident involved multiple drones and ballistic missiles, some of which were intercepted by Saudi air defenses, though debris caused damage to the airport perimeter.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this development is significant as it highlights the volatile security environment in the Horn of Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. Many Somalis reside and work in Saudi Arabia, and any escalation in the conflict could affect their safety and travel. Additionally, the Houthi-Iran alliance continues to shape regional dynamics that impact Somalia, including arms smuggling and political interference.\n\nThe attack also undermines recent diplomatic efforts by the United Nations to broker a lasting peace in Yemen. The informal truce had allowed for reduced hostilities and some humanitarian relief, but the latest violence threatens to reverse those gains.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/14/xuutiyiinta-oo-jebisay-xabbad-joojin-4-sano-ah-kadib-weerarkii-abha/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=xuutiyiinta-oo-jebisay-xabbad-joojin-4-sano-ah-kadib-weerarkii-abha",
